\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 You're missing the point. According to physicalism, consciousness emerges from the interaction of physical particles. Those particles behave according to mechanistic physical laws. Consciousness cannot affect the particles. So what you experience has no causal power over your behavior. There's no necessity for your phenomenal experience of pain to lead to a particular behavioral outcome. In fact, according to physicalists, it doesn't. You just happen to feel pain when your behavior is avoidant. This is the "harmony" they're speaking about. For some reason our phenomenal experience matches the narrative of what is happening around us.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 That's an epiphenomenalist account, but I don't think most physicalists are epiphenomenalists for consciousness. Consciousness is an emergent behaviour, true, but it's still physical.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Consider the pressure or temperature of a gas, they are emergent properties but we have no problem saying that the pressure or temperature of the gas had this or that causal effect. That's because the temperature and pressure are generalisations of actual causal behaviours. It's the same for consciousness.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 When you say "}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Those particles behave according to mechanistic physical laws}{\f0\fs24\b0 ", that behaviour and the transformation of information that's going on is consciousness. It makes no sense to then say that "}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Consciousness cannot affect the particles}{\f0\fs24\b0 ', you're effectively saying that the behaviour of the particles cannot affect the particles.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 You're applying a dualist mode of thinking, considering consciousness to be separate from the particles and their behaviour. That's not the physicalist view.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 "Consciousness" is not a visible output in the same way that the actual new physical configuration is. We can't know if a specific transformation actually gives rise to subjective experience.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 We experience it, and that's an observation we have. We can't observe that inner experience in others, but that doesn't make our experience any less valid as an observation. Also there are some who think that we can come up with an observational test for consciousness, I think that's mistaken.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Let's suppose consciousness is computational. Can we construct an observational tests for arbitrary computations? It turns out no, we can't. Church and Turing proved this in the 1930s. There are many computations that cannot be characterised without actually performing the computation. So if consciousness is a computation, it's highly likely it's in the class of computations that cannot be observationally characterised.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 We can't know if a specific transformation actually gives rise to subjective experience.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Well, sucks to be us. It would be nice if everything in the world was observationally provable, but it turns out that's not the case.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 The specific transformation of information is an interpretation\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 we}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~give to the transformation.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Let's take a robot mapping it's environment with sensors, then using that map to successfully navigate through a maze, say. That's an objective observable behaviour. However there is no objective test for observing the activity in a computer and determining that what it's doing is navigating through an environment. Let's say we got hold of a robot built by aliens, we might never figure out what it's doing just by looking at the internal states of the computer. However if we observed it performing some task, we would know that it must be performing the calculations to enable that task.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 So I think we agree there is a necessary connection between performance of a computation and the activity of the particles performing the computation, the question is interpretation. You say.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 The actual transformation is just the physical changes taking place.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 I'm a physicalist, so, sure but the physical doesn't just consist of objects sitting in space. It consists of their processes and transformations, and their informational relations. That's all physical too.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The fact that a map corresponds to an environment and enables a process of navigation is a physical fact about the world. That it enables effective navigation is objectively observable. The fact that a neural network AI can successfully strategise in order to achieve a spectacularly complex goal such as beat a Grandmaster at chess is a physical fact about the world.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The physicalist view is that the fact that a biological neural network can construct effective psychological models of the world and itself, and internally reflect on those states in order to contemplate it's own nature is a fact about the world.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 There's no objective way to interpret this physical change to have some sort of necessary subjective\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 meaning}{\f0\fs24\b0 .}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 We can see that meaning can consist of achieving an intentional outcome, and automatic systems are objectively entirely capable of doing this.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The usual move at this point is to say that, ah but these systems are only doing what we tell them to do. That's not intentionality. Then I would point out that we're the products of evolution, and our intentions are derived from evolutionary imperatives. Just to skip forward a bit.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 "No one honestly believes that the world has no meaning"}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 It has meaning\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 to me}{\f0\fs24\b0 . Adding a creator to the universe doesn't imbue it with any more meaning, because by that logic, without a creator, God has no purpose and no meaning.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \line }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 My shoe fits neatly in my footprints, but I would be hard pressed to call that evidence of "orthophysical harmony". It seems more reasonable to view such elegant relationships as a result of cause and effect, or physical properties that interact.\~}{ }
