\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 The paper seems to be largely framed as an argument against some sort of dualist naturalist.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 But I would argue that\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_physicalism"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 reductive materialism}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~has no problem explaining what they're trying to explain. The "correlation" of phenomenal states with physical states is not at all "fortunate", if those physical states are just what phenomenal states\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 are}{\f0\fs24\b0 .}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The correlation of phenomenal/physical states with one another would be explained by evolution. If a creature has a bunch of neurons just firing randomly with no rhyme or reason, that's probably not going to help them survive. But if some sensory perception causes neurons to fire, and this causes a chain of neurons to fire in a way that ends with sending signals to other body parts to respond appropriately given the perception, that's certainly going to give a survival advantage, and mutations that correspond to this will be selected for. This is evolution 101.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 So it would be more strange if we\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 don't}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~see this correlation under physicalism.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The paper does mention evolution, but says that an evolutionary explanation would "presuppose normative harmony", which it doesn't, and arguably reductive materialism is much more consistent with evolution than any other view is (whether that's within atheism or theism).}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 But their fundamental logic here seems to be something like this:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 My car has been stolen.}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 Any one of 8 billion people could've stolen my car, or it could've been magic (and we consider P(stolen|person) versus P(stolen|magic)).}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 It's unlikely that any of some 7.9 billion people would've stolen the car, on account of not being anywhere near the vicinity at the time.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 Let's consider people living in my city. For one such person, we have video evidence of them breaking into my car and driving away with it. If we suppose they stole it, this does a good job of explaining where my car went...}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 But, I have "no reason to think that this highly specific city person should cover a large fraction of the person region of our probability space" (i.e. it's just 1 of billions of people, which is a small probability).}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 So "we can't infer that P(stolen|person) is high".}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0 Therefore it was probably magic.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 This is clearly absurd. They're arguing that other atheist views are unlikely, and then they're using that to infer that this other atheist view must also be unlikely, even though they literally just argued that it's the one that makes the most sense.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \~}{\f0\fs24\b1 because identity theory says literally the exact opposite of that - identity theory says that mental states are identical to certain physical states, so you can't have those physical states without having mental states. What they're saying is essentially "since identity theory is false, evolution can't explain identity theory", which is meaningless and nonsensical circularity. }
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 so in art, to have these rules, these, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93this is what you should do to produce this effect\u8221\'94 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 its the worst crime. Almost a moral failing. And this gets to a great fear - my internal states are so dramatically diffferent that it will resonate with no one.}}